title: For Sale:  Completely new P14.45 Para-Ordnance Stainless + Factory Extras
location: West Side of Evansville, Evansville, Indiana
postcontent:
On March 30, 1981 a mentally ill John Hinckley Jr. attempted to assassinate then President Ronald Reagan only 69 days into his presidency with a 22 caliber Röhm RG-14 revolver he purchased at a pawn shop.  Hinckley fired all 6 .22lr cartridges from his pistol in 1.7 seconds hitting James Brady directly in the head, District of Columbia police officer Thomas Delahanty in the back of his neck, Secret Service agent Timothy McCarthy in the abdomen, and President Reagan with his 6th shot after it ricocheted off the armored side of the limousine and hit the president in his left underarm, grazing a rib and lodging in his lung, stopping only 1 inch from his heart. The 3rd and 5th bullets did not hit any people.

The 6th shot that ended up hitting Reagan pierced his lung and created heavy internal bleeding. Prompt medical attention not only saved his life, but allowed him to maintain control of his office despite Secretary of State Alexander Haig incorrectly stating that he was "in control here" at the time.  The police officer, Thomas Delahanty, recovered but had to retire due to his wound and Secret Service agent, Timothy McCarthy, who was protecting Reagan with his body, fully recovered.  Sadly, James Brady, the White House Press Secretary under U.S. President Ronald Reagan suffered a very serious head wound that left him paralyzed and permanently disabled.  

Hinckley got off, in my opinion, way too easily because he claimed that watching the movie "Taxi Driver" with Robert Di Nero and Jodie Foster nearly 20 times caused him to become mentally ill due to 'erotomania' and a liberal Federal District Judge Barrington D. Parker received thousands of letters protesting his 'acquittal' of Hinckley due to his insanity plea.  This all leads up to why I purchased this pistol shortly after it was manufactured in 1996.  Rather than work to change the legal system "loopholes" that allowed Hinckley to be acquitted due to a plea of insanity (and never took the stand at his trial at the advice of his attorneys), Sarah Brady made it her lifelong goal to try to remove firearms from the public.

Our next president, George H. W. Bush, was hammered by two things; not 'finishing the job' in Iraq and mostly for refusing to allow any Brady Bill, Brady Law, Assault Weapons Ban etc. to ever get passed.  Bush went on record calling for our government to "Go after the criminal not the gun owner".  Never before had Democrats used the proposition of new gun laws as a campaign tactic for the office of President of the United States.  Bill Clinton certainly did, with great success, putting Sarah Brady on the microphone to tell of the evils of guns.  Obviously it worked for Slick Willy who, previously with his extremely shady past, was not even considered a reasonable contender.  The public had successfully been turned on firearms!  Never mind that on February 28, 1993 Janet Reno, with Clinton's full backing, murdered Seventy-six people, including 21 children and two pregnant women, along with Davidian leader David Koresh in Waco, TX.  Clinton reasoned "that was justified" because they "had guns"!  On November 30, 1993 Clinton got both houses to pass the Brady Bill and Assault Weapons Bill a year later leaving gun owners suddenly faced wide spread new laws greatly restricting firearms.  Clinton got re-elected despite turning the White House into the Playboy Mansion East and things looked dim for supporters of the 2nd Amendment.

All that is precisely WHY I purchased quite a few brand new high capacity firearms at that time while I still could and simply bought more safes to put them in so they could remain pristine in climate controlled conditions.  This Para-Ordnance P.14 .45ACP is a perfect example of what was (and likely will again be) targeted by the government.  I used the 'coupon' to purchase two additional high capacity magazines from Para-Ordnance, which are still in their original wrapper and included in this deal.  The firearm has positively never had a round chambered in it and likely has only been out of my safe once or twice prior to taking the pics for this ad.  I also spent well over $100, at the time, to purchase a 4th factory Para-Ordnance magazine that has a different footplate and holds 15 rounds, which is still in it's original wrapper and clearly marked as such by Para.  It's all here and any tiny marks on the pistol would be ones from the factory in getting to the gun store and to my safe.

Needless to say, there are very, very few 100% pristine high capacity .45 ACP 1911 style pistols still out there from the Clinton era.  I will sell face to face to another buyer in Evansville, IN or, for $40 plus the cost of insurance, ship to an FFL dealer.  Payment must be in cash or by USPS money orders.  No exceptions.  Now you have the full background.  Are you ready to own a piece of history?  Any questions, just ask.  Want more pics, just ask.

title: For Sale/Trade:  RARE Winchester Model 50 Featherweight 12 gauge auto-loading shotgun
postcontent:
For sale or trade is a Winchester Model 50 Featherweight 12 gauge auto-loading shotgun. 

Winchester only produced 196,400 Model 50s between 1954 and 1961, and very few (<50,000) examples of the Featherweight between 1958 and 1960, making this a rare and collectible piece. Winchester stopped production because it was too expensive to manufacture, and the profit margin per unit was too low.   A true “pre-64 Winchester”, the Model 50 is considered a well built and reliable shotgun – it has all machined parts and no stamped, cast or plastic anywhere. It is a short bolt blowback action with a floating chamber, and the first production autoloader with a non-recoiling barrel (the Browning A5 and the Remington 48 have recoiling barrels). The rare featherweight model replaced the steel frame and trigger group with an aluminum alloy; the Model 50 Featherweight swings and tracks quickly, making it a favorite with many champion skeet and trap shooters. 

This particular shotgun was manufactured in late 1959 and features a 28 inch full fixed choke barrel and walnut “field grade” stocks with factory hand-cut checkering. The action is fully functional; I had it out last autumn and shot a full round of skeet without any malfunctions. The stock is free of cracks, chips, deep scratches, or gouges but may have some light handling marks. There is no rust, pitting, or cracks in the metal. The bluing is 90 – 95% with some lightening around the base of the barrel. There are some light handling marks on the receiver, and one small ¼ inch scratch near the ejection port. The bore is near perfect. This gun does not look to have been used much - this is a NICE gun. I am only selling to thin out my shotgun collection.

Add this rare Winchester to your collection, or take it into the field next season! 

FTF only with bill of sale.
